04501nam a22005295i 9780774854245DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19811981xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748542457 a10.59962/97807748542452doi  a(DE-B1597)661207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1060.8 ǂb M39 1981eb 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a917.12/04100aOverland from Canada to British Columbia :bBy Mr. Thomas McMicking of Queenston, Canada West /ced. by Joanne Leduc. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[1981] 4c©1981  a1 online resource (165 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Pioneers of British Columbia00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tCredits -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tWilliam G.R. Hind: The “Expedition Artist” -- tA Note on the Text -- tTo the Editor of the British Columbian -- tA Note on the McMicking Family -- tA Note on the Trail -- tNotes to the Introduction -- tNotes to William G.R. Hind -- tNotes to the Text -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tThe Pioneers of British Columbia0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpurred on by reports of gold in the Cariboo, adventurers from all over the world descended on British Columbia in the mid-1800s. Among them were ambitious easterners who accepted the challenge of the shorter but more arduous overland route across the prairies and the Rockies. One such man determined to find his fortune in the West was Thomas McMicking -- destined to lead the largest and best organized group of 'Overlanders' into British Columbia. His record of their epic journey is a valuable historical document that possesses the universal appeal of an adventure story. McMicking presents a vivid image of the hardships of the overland route, the dangers, both real and imagined -- like the apparently threatening Plains Indians who turned out to be 'our best friends' -- facts about important officials and settlements, and scientific observations of the physical environment. But this is also a very human document that describes a journey of self- discovery revealing a sensitive man's encounter with a bountiful and beautiful yet hostile and alien land. The journal is augmented by a valuable introduction, appendices on the Overlanders' trail and the McMicking family, and biographical sketches of many of the men who later played prominent roles in British Columbia's development and whose descendants became some of the province's best-known leaders and families. It is also enriched by the pictorial records of William Hind, a major Canadian painter who became known as the 'expedition artist.' Drawing on much previously unavailable material as well as on traditional sources, the editor has created a comprehensive historical framework for this unique document.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh1 aLeduc, Joanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485424540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774854245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774854245/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  University of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles